'''York City Football Club''' is an [[England|English]] [[football (soccer)|football]] club based in [[York]]. The club participates in the [[Conference National]], the fifth tier of English football. Founded in 1922, they joined [[the Football League]] in 1929, and have spent most of their history in the lower divisions. The club briefly rose as high as the second tier of English football, spending two seasons in the [[Football League Second Division|Second Division]] in the 1970s. At the end of the [[2003-04 in English football|2003–04]] season the club lost their League status when they were [[Promotion and relegation|relegated]] from the [[Football League Third Division|Third Division]], and have since remained in the Conference.

York have enjoyed more success in cup competitions than in the league, with highlights including an [[FA Cup]] semi-final appearance in 1955. In the [[1995-96 in English football|1995–96]] [[Football League Cup|League Cup]], York beat [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] 3–0 at [[Old Trafford (football ground)|Old Trafford]];  Manchester United went on to win the [[FA Cup]] and [[Premier League|Premiership]] [[The Double#The English Double|double]] that season.

York play their home games at [[KitKat Crescent]] in York. This stadium was formerly known as Bootham Crescent, but was renamed KitKat Crescent as part of a sponsorship deal with [[Nestlé]], whose confectionery factory, formerly known as [[Rowntree's]], is one of the city's largest employers.

==History==
{{details|History of York City F.C.}}
:''For information on the current season, see [[York City F.C. season 2007-08]] or for previous years see [[York City F.C. seasons]].''

York City Football Club was first founded in 1908 as an amateur side,<ref name="Complete record">{{cite book
 | last = Batters
 | first = Dave
 | title = York City: A Complete Record 1922-1990
 | publisher = The Breedon Books Publishing Company Limited
 | year = 1990
 | pages = p9
 | chapter = The York City Story
 | isbn = 0907969690 }}</ref> although some sources state the roots of the club can be traced as far back as 1897 when the [[York Football League|York and District League]] was formed.<ref name="York City FC: history">{{cite web
| title = York City FC: history
| url = http://www.bbc.co.uk/northyorkshire/content/articles/2005/09/15/york_city_history_sport_feature.shtml 
| publisher = BBC North Yorkshire
| accessdate = 2007-03-25}}</ref> The club joined the [[Northern League (football)|Northern League]] in 1908, but left after two seasons to form the Yorkshire Combination (a proto-[[Yorkshire Football League|Yorkshire League]]). The club turned professional in 1912 and joined the [[Midland Football League|Midland League]], where they played for three seasons, rising as high as tenth position.  They played their final season in [[1914-15 in English football|1914–15]] before folding in 1917 during the [[First World War]].<ref name="YORK CITY{1}">{{cite web
| title = YORK CITY{1}
| url = http://www.fchd.info/YORKC-1.HTM
| publisher = Football Club History Database
| accessdate = 2007-07-04}}</ref>

[[Image:YCFC1922.jpg|right|thumb|York City squad of 1922.]]
The club was re-founded in 1922 by members of the former club. These members founded a [[limited company]] and gained admission to the [[Midland Football League|Midland League]] where they played in  for seven seasons, achieving a highest finish of sixth, in both [[1924-25 in English football|1924–25]] and [[1926-27 in English football|1926–27]].<ref name="York City historical">{{cite web
| title = York City
| url = http://www.historicalkits.co.uk/York_City/York_City.htm
| publisher = HistoricKits.co.uk
| accessdate = 2007-07-04}}</ref><ref name="YORK CITY">{{cite web
| title = YORK CITY
| url = http://www.fchd.info/YORKC.HTM 
| publisher = Football Club History Database
| accessdate = 2007-03-26}}</ref> York were elected to [[the Football League]] in 1929,<ref name="Brief History">{{cite web
| title = Brief History
| url = http://www.yorkcityfc.com/history/brief_history.php
| publisher = Red and Blue NET
| accessdate = 2007-03-30}}</ref> and spent the following 22 seasons in [[Football League Third Division North|Division Three North]], from [[1929-30 in English football|1929–30]] to [[1957-58 in English football|1957–58]]. The club ended the majority of seasons in the bottom half of the table until the 1950s, when they reached fourth in both the [[1952-53 in English football|1952–53]] and [[1954-55 in English football|1954–55]] seasons.<ref name="Brief History"/>

The club fared better in cup competitions and built a reputation for "''giant killing''",<ref name="City's Cup History">{{cite web
| title = City's Cup History
| url = http://www.ycfc.net/about-york-city/citys-cup-history.php
| publisher = York City FC
| accessdate = 2007-03-30}}</ref> the earliest example being in the [[1937-38 in English football|1937–38]] season [[FA Cup]] tournament, when the club, then playing in the [[Football League Third Division|Third Division]], managed to knock out [[Football League First Division|First Division]] [[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Bromwich Albion]] and [[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]].  They met [[Huddersfield Town F.C.|Huddersfield Town]] in the quarter-finals which was drawn 0–0, before losing the [[Replay (football)|replay]] 2–1 at [[Leeds Road]].<ref name="Brief History"/> The club's longest cup run came when they reached the FA Cup semi-final in the [[1954-55 in English football|1954–55]] season, a campaign in which [[Arthur Bottom]] scored eight goals for the club, and the team eliminated a [[Blackpool F.C.|Blackpool]] side featuring [[Stanley Matthews]].<ref name="York City FC: history">{{cite web
| title = York City FC: history
| url = http://www.bbc.co.uk/northyorkshire/content/articles/2005/09/15/york_city_history_sport_feature.shtml 
| publisher = BBC North Yorkshire
| accessdate = 2007-03-25}}</ref> In the semi-final, York drew 1–1 with [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]], taking the tie to a replay, in which City were defeated 2–0.<ref name="Brief History"/>

In 1958, York became founding members of the Fourth Division, as the Third Divisions North and [[Football League Third Division South|South]] were restructured into new Third and [[Football League Fourth Division|Fourth]] divisions, based on league positions at the end of the [[1957-58 in English football|1957–58]] season. They missed out on the runner-up spot in the inaugural season only on [[goal difference|goal average]], and were promoted to the [[Football League Third Division|Third Division]] in third place,<ref name="Final 1958/1959 English Division 4 Table">{{cite web
| title = Final 1958/1959 English Division 4 Table
| url = http://www.soccerbase.com/league2.sd?competitionid=7&seasonid=88&teamid=2910 
| publisher = Soccerbase
| accessdate = 2007-07-20}}</ref> but were relegated back after just one season.<ref name="Final 1959/1960 English Division 3 (old) Table">{{cite web
| title = Final 1959/1960 English Division 3 (old) Table
| url = http://www.soccerbase.com/league2.sd?competitionid=7&seasonid=89&teamid=2910
| publisher = Soccerbase
| accessdate = 2007-07-20}}</ref> A second promotion in [[1964-65 in English football|1964–65]], again in third place in the Fourth Division,<ref name="Final 1964/1965 English Division 4 Table">{{cite web
| title = Final 1964/1965 English Division 4 Table
| url = http://www.soccerbase.com/league2.sd?competitionid=7&seasonid=94&teamid=2910
| publisher = Soccerbase
| accessdate = 2007-07-20}}</ref> saw a similar instant relegation back from the Third Division the next season.<ref name="Final 1965/1966 English Division 3 (old) Table">{{cite web
| title = Final 1965/1966 English Division 3 (old) Table
| url = http://www.soccerbase.com/league2.sd?competitionid=7&seasonid=95&teamid=2910
| publisher = Soccerbase
| accessdate = 2007-07-20}}</ref> York's record of promotion every six years was maintained by a team sporting the future [[England national football team|England]] forward [[Phil Boyer]] in [[1970-71 in English football|1970–71]],<ref name="Final 1970/1971 English Division 4 Table">{{cite web
| title = Final 1970/1971 English Division 4 Table
| url = http://www.soccerbase.com/league2.sd?competitionid=7&seasonid=100&teamid=2910
| publisher = Soccerbase
| accessdate = 2007-07-25}}</ref><ref name="Phil Boyer">{{cite web
| title = Phil Boyer
| url = http://www.sporting-heroes.net/football-heroes/displayhero_club.asp?HeroID=231
| publisher = Football-Heroes
| accessdate = 2007-07-25}}</ref> and this time the team managed to stay in the Third Division, albeit only on goal average in both the next two seasons.<ref name="Final 1971/1972 English Division 3 (old) Table">{{cite web
| title = Final 1971/1972 English Division 3 (old) Table
| url = http://www.soccerbase.com/league2.sd?competitionid=7&seasonid=101&teamid=2910
| publisher = Soccerbase
| accessdate = 2007-07-25}}</ref><ref name="Final 1972/1973 English Division 3 (old) Table">{{cite web
| title = Final 1972/1973 English Division 3 (old) Table
| url = http://www.soccerbase.com/league2.sd?competitionid=7&seasonid=102&teamid=2910
| publisher = Soccerbase
| accessdate = 2007-07-25}}</ref>

After these two seasons the team hit form in the [[1973-74 in English football|1973–74]] season, when "three up, three down" promotion and relegation was introduced to the Football League. After being among the leaders all season York City were eventually promoted to [[Football League Second Division|Division Two]] in third place.  Their first season in the Second Division saw York finish in their highest ever league position, 15th place.<ref name="Brief History"/>  On [[March 29]], [[1975]], they played in front of the highest ever League crowd to see them &ndash; 46,802 at [[Old Trafford (football ground)|Old Trafford]] in a 2–1 defeat to [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]]. The following season York finished in 21st place in the Second Division and were relegated back to the Third Division.<ref name="Brief History"/>  Under former Manchester United manager [[Wilf McGuinness]], the club dropped further still, into Division Four in the [[1976-77 in English football|1976–77]] season after finishing bottom of the Third Division. In the [[1981-82 in English football|1981–82]] season, York failed to win in 12 home games, a club record, and lost to non-league side [[Altrincham F.C.|Altrincham]] in the FA Cup. <!--not necessary in history section really...
Keith Walwyn was signed during this season, and became York's first player to top 20 goals in a season since the 1970s. -->In the [[1983-84 in English football|1983–84]] season York won the Fourth Division with a record 101 points,<ref name="Brief History"/> the first team to do so in the Football League.<ref name="Football League points records">{{cite web
| title = Football League points records
| url = http://www.football-league.premiumtv.co.uk/page/RecordPoints/0,,10794,00.html
| publisher = The Football League
| accessdate = 2007-04-30}}</ref> In January 1985, York City recorded a shock result in the Fourth Round of the FA Cup by beating [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] 1–0 at Bootham Crescent, courtesy of a penalty from [[Keith Houchen]].<ref name="York 1 Arsenal 0">{{cite web
| title = York 1 Arsenal 0
| url = http://www.yorkcityfc.com/history/arsenal.php
| publisher = Red and Blue NET
| accessdate = 2007-03-31}}</ref> York proceeded to draw 1–1 with [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] at Bootham Crescent on [[16 February]] [[1985]], but lost 7–0 in the replay at [[Anfield]], York's record cup defeat.<ref name="Brief History"/>

[[Image:YorkCityvEverton.jpg|left|thumb|130px|City players celebrate after scoring against Everton in 1996.]]
In 1993 York ended a five year spell in the Third Division by gaining promotion to the [[Football League Second Division|Second Division]] via the playoffs, beating [[Crewe Alexandra F.C.|Crewe Alexandra]] on penalties in the final at [[Wembley Stadium (1923)|Wembley Stadium]].<ref name="League Two Play-Off - Final">{{cite web
| title = League Two Play-Off - Final
| url = http://www.soccerbase.com/results3.sd?gameid=389904
| publisher = Soccerbase
| accessdate = 2007-07-21}}</ref> York stayed in the Second Division for six seasons, during which they reached the playoffs in their first season, but lost to [[Stockport County F.C.|Stockport County]] in the semi-finals.<ref name="Brief History"/>

York recorded a shock victory in the [[1995-96 in English football|1995–96]] [[Football League Cup|League Cup]] Second Round, when they beat Manchester United 3–0 at Old Trafford.<ref name="When City rocked the world">{{cite web
| title = When City rocked the world
| url = http://www.yorkpress.co.uk/archive/library2005/ycfcoldtrafford/display.var.936400.0.when_city_rocked_the_world.php
| publisher = The Press
| accessdate = 2007-03-26}}</ref>  York then went on to beat [[Everton F.C.|Everton]] in the Second Round of the League Cup the following season in 1996.<ref name="Brief History"/> They drew the first leg 1–1 at [[Goodison Park]], <!--too much detail? with Neil Tolson taking the lead for York but [[Andrei Kanchelskis]] pulled one back for Everton.-->but won the second leg 3–2 at [[KitKat Crescent|Bootham Crescent]]<!-- too much detail?, where York won the game 3–2 with [[Graeme Murty]] scoring the goal which separated the two sides-->.<ref name="York City v Everton">{{cite web
| title = York City v Everton
| url = http://www.toffeeweb.com/SEASON/96-97/reports/yorkct_a.htm
| publisher = ToffeeWeb
| accessdate = 2007-03-26}}</ref>

[[Image:Chris Brass.jpg|thumb|right|[[Chris Brass]] hugs [[Viv Busby]] after a win for York City in 2004.]]
In December 2001, long-serving chairman [[Douglas Craig]] put the club and its ground up for sale for £4.5 million, announcing that unless a new owner was found before [[April 1]], [[2002]], York City would be withdrawn from the Football League.<ref name="Reynolds to York's rescue">{{cite news
| title = Reynolds to York's rescue
