Throughout the majority of the history of the club, York City have worn red shirts with white shorts. However, in the club's first season, [[1922-23 in English football|1922–23]], maroon shirts were worn, with white shorts and black socks. Moreover, in the 1930s, York changed their maroon jerseys to chocolate and cream stripes, a reference to the city's association with the confectionery industry. After five years they changed their colours to what were described as "distinctive red shirts", with the official explanation that the striped jerseys clashed with opponents too often. To mark York's promotion to the Second Division in 1974, a bold white "Y" was added to the teams shirts, with the club coming to be referred to as the "Y-fronts". In 1979, red shirts returned, along with navy shorts.<ref name="York City historical"/>

In June 2003, York City agreed a deal for [[Nike, Inc.|Nike]] to provide the club's kits.<ref name="Minstermen agree Nike deal">{{cite news
| title = Minstermen agree Nike deal
| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/y/york_city/2975710.stm
| publisher = BBC Sport
| date = [[2003-06-09]]
| accessdate = 2007-03-23}}</ref> Since 2004, the club has dropped navy from the kits and instead use plain red and white.<ref name="York City historical"/> Though a sizeable proportion of the fans are unhappy with the navy being dropped.

Currently the club have also brought in a third kit in the form of a light blue shirt and socks, with maroon shorts. In pre-season friendlies it has been used in place of the usual away kit.<ref name="City Launch New Third Kit">{{cite web
| title = City Launch New Third Kit
| url = http://www.ycfc.net/news/august07/1.php
| publisher = York City FC
| accessdate = 2007-08-08}}</ref>

==Stadia==
{{details|KitKat Crescent}}
[[Image:Kit kat cres 07.jpg|right|thumb|250px|KitKat Crescent in 2007.]]
Between 1921 and 1932, York City played their home games at [[Fulfordgate]].<ref name="Fulfordgate">{{cite web
| title = Fulfordgate
| url = http://www.soccerbase.com/grounds2.sd?groundid=112
| publisher = soccerbase
| accessdate = 2007-03-26}}</ref> York purchased the land for Bootham Crescent, a former cricket ground, in summer 1932, as it was closer to the club's centre of support and the railway station than Fulfordgate. Bootham Crescent was converted into a football ground; a main stand was built and a roof was erected above the Popular stand. The ground opened on [[31 August]] [[1932]]. In March 1938, the ground's record attendance was set when 28,123 people watched York City play [[Huddersfield Town F.C.|Huddersfield Town]].<ref name="The History of Bootham Crescent">{{cite web
| title = The History of Bootham Crescent
| url = http://www.yorkcityfc.com/club/bc_history.php
| publisher = Red and Blue NET
| accessdate = 2007-03-26}}</ref> 

Bootham Crescent was damaged during [[World War II]] when a bomb landed on the Shipton Street End, but shortly after the war ended, the terracing was laid properly with concrete. At this point most of the ground was still uncovered. The stadium was fitted with floodlights in 1959, which were used for the first time in a friendly against [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]] on [[28 October]], [[1959]].<ref name="The History of Bootham Crescent"/>

During the mid-1980s, £300,000 was spent on a series of improvements to the Bootham Crescent ground, which was funded by money generated during York City's [[FA Cup]] run in the [[1984-85 in English football|1984–85]] season, which included games against [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] and then [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]], including a replay at Liverpool in front of a crowd of 43,000. The improvements included building hospitality suites behind the main stand, new club offices, turnstiles, new crush barriers, and the addition of more seats to the Popular Stand, giving a seating capacity of 2,883 seats out of a total capacity of 13,185.<ref name="The History of Bootham Crescent"/>

The capacity of Bootham Crescent had at one time been 12,475, with 3,245 seats, but this was reduced in 1994 because of an increase to the family area of the Main stand due to popular demand, and alterations to enable the ground to comply with the recommendations made in the [[Taylor Report]]. It saw 326 seats replacing a standing area, reducing capacity. Stricter rules concerning the density of people standing resulting from the Taylor Report further reduced capacity.<ref name="The History of Bootham Crescent"/>

New floodlights were installed during the summer of 1995, costing £122,000. These floodlights are twice as bright as the original floodlights, and meet the requirements for Division One football. A drainage system was installed to improve the quality of the pitch during winter, costing several thousand pounds. A water tower was also installed in the late 1990s.<ref name="The History of Bootham Crescent"/>

York had planned a move to [[Huntington Stadium]] in 2003, but withdrew their application as they were given a loan of £2 million from the Football Stadia Improvement Fund, which secured the purchase of Bootham Crescent.<ref name="Spread the news on new York City">{{cite news
| title = Spread the news on new York City
| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/y/york_city/6503459.stm
| publisher = BBC Sport
| date = [[2007-03-28]]
| accessdate = 2007-03-28}}</ref>  In January 2005, following a sponsorship deal with [[Nestlé]], Bootham Crescent was renamed [[Kit Kat|KitKat]] Crescent.<ref name="KitKat Crescent">{{cite news
| title = KitKat Crescent
| url = http://www.bbc.co.uk/northyorkshire/sport/2005/01/19/kitkat.shtml
| publisher = BBC North Yorkshire
| date = [[2005-01-19]]
| accessdate = 2007-03-26}}</ref> The ground currently holds a capacity of 9,034.<ref name="York City ground"/>

===New stadium===
On [[4 February]] [[2004]], the club's board announced that an agreement had been reached which would see York City remain at Bootham Crescent until 2015.<ref name="The History of Bootham Crescent"/> York's board revealed in February 2007 that the club are hoping the move to a new ground can be completed within five years.<ref name="Speed is the essential key for City’s new ground">{{cite news
| title = Speed is the essential key for City’s new ground
| url = http://www.yorkpress.co.uk/sport/yorkcityfc/news/display.var.1226815.0.speed_is_the_essential_key_for_citys_new_ground.php
| publisher = The Press
| date = [[2007-03-01]]
| accessdate = 2007-03-01}}</ref> It is hoped that the new stadium will not just provide a home for York City, but can also be used as a concert venue.<ref name="Crunch talks loom over new 'iconic' city stadium">{{cite news
| title = Crunch talks loom over new 'iconic' city stadium
| url = http://www.yorkpress.co.uk/search/display.var.1191854.0.crunch_talks_loom_over_new_iconic_city_stadium.php
| publisher = The Press
| date = [[2007-02-14]]
| accessdate = 2007-06-08}}</ref> It is to be built on either the British Sugar factory site, York Central or land north of the Nestlé complex.<ref name="York City FC on verge of stadium deal">{{cite news
| title = York City FC on verge of stadium deal
| url = http://www.yorkpress.co.uk/sport/yorkcityfc/news/display.var.1307188.0.york_city_fc_on_verge_of_stadium_deal.php
| publisher = The Press
| date = [[2007-04-04]]
| accessdate = 2007-04-20}}</ref>

The new stadium will be similar to [[Princes Park, Dartford|Princes Park]] of [[Dartford F.C.|Dartford FC]], but will hold a larger capacity. Steve Galloway, City of York Council leader, said his aspiration was for a 10,000-seater stadium to be built, which would be home to both York City and [[York City Knights]], although, speaking at the launch of his party's election manifesto on [[3 April]], [[2007]], he said it may be smaller initially, at 6,000 or 7,000 seats.<ref name="York City FC on verge of stadium deal"/>

==Supporters and rivalries==
York City is one of the best supported clubs in the Conference National, with an average home attendance of 3,054 for the [[2006-07 in English football|2006–07]] season.<ref name="Bootham Crescent">{{cite web
| title = Bootham Crescent
| url = http://www.soccerbase.com/grounds2.sd?groundid=43
| publisher = soccerbase
| accessdate = 2007-04-02}}</ref> The club has a number of domestic supporters' groups, including Harrogate Minstermen and the Jorvik Reds.<ref name="Jorvik Reds">{{cite web
| title = Jorvik Reds
| url = http://www.ycfc.net/jorvik-reds.php
| publisher = York City FC
| accessdate = 2007-04-02}}</ref> The [[York Nomad Society]] is the hooligan firm associated with the club.<ref name="Hooligan Firms">{{cite web
| title = Hooligan Firms
| url = http://www.ave-it.net/hooligan_firms.htm
| publisher = Ave-it.net
| accessdate = 2007-04-03}}</ref> Like some other professional football clubs in England, York City has a small number of fans who have had Banning Orders placed on them by the club for unreasonable behaviour.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.homeoffice.gov.uk/documents/football-arrests-0506?view=Binary
|title = Football Banning Orders by club supported (10 October 2006) |accessdate = 2007-07-25 |date = [[2006-10-21]] |format = PDF |work = Statistics on Football related arrests & Banning Orders - Season 2005-6|publisher = Home Office |pages = page 4 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.homeoffice.gov.uk/documents/football-arrests-0506?view=Binary
|title = Football Banning Orders by club supported (10 October 2006) |accessdate = 2007-07-25 |date = [[2006-10-21]] |format = PDF |work = Statistics on Football related arrests & Banning Orders - Season 2005-6|publisher = Home Office |pages = page 13 }}</ref>

For home games, the club produces an "Official Match programme", which consists of 48 pages and is sold for £2.50. The club is also the subject of an independent supporters' [[fanzine]], ''Ginner's Left Foot'', which was launched in February 2002.<ref name="Club Guide">{{cite web
| title = Club Guide
| url = http://york.rivals.net/default.asp?sid=973&p=2&stid=8247049
| publisher = Minstermen.net
| accessdate = 2007-04-02}}</ref> [[John Sentamu|Dr. John Sentamu]], the [[Archbishop of York]], became the patron to York City for the [[2007-08 in English football|2007–08]] season, after purchasing a season ticket in May 2007.<ref name="Minster Man Becomes York City’s Patron">{{cite news
| title = Minster Man Becomes York City’s Patron
| url = http://www.ycfc.net/news/july07/1.php
| publisher = York City FC
| date = [[2007-07-02]]
| accessdate = 2007-07-05}}</ref>

Traditionally, York City's two main rivalries have been with [[Scarborough F.C.|Scarborough]] and [[Hull City A.F.C.|Hull City]].<ref name="Rivalry Uncovered!">{{Cite web
| url = http://www.footballfanscensus.com/issueresults/Club_Rivalries_Uncovered_Results.pdf
| title = Rivalry Uncovered!
| accessdate = 2007-07-25
| publisher = The [[Football Fans Census]]
}}</ref> The rivalry between Hull and York is represented by a battle between [[lion]] (York City's mascot) and [[tiger]] (Hull City's mascot), but in recent times the clubs have played in different league and so it has not been as intense. To a lesser extent there are also local rivalries with [[Doncaster Rovers F.C.|Doncaster Rovers]], [[Darlington F.C.|Darlington]], [[Hartlepool United F.C.|Hartlepool United]] and more recently one with [[Greater Manchester]] side [[Bury F.C.|Bury]].<ref name="York City ground"/>

==Statistics and records==
{{details|York City F.C. records}}
[[Barry Jackson (footballer)|Barry Jackson]] holds the record for York City appearances, having played 539 matches. Former defender [[Andy McMillan]] comes second, having played 492 matches. The record for a goalkeeper is held by [[Tommy Forgan]], with 428 appearances.<ref name="Record Appearances for York City">{{cite web
| title = Record Appearances for York City
| url = http://www.rivals.net/default.asp?sid=973&p=2&stid=8192749
| publisher = Minstermen.net
| accessdate = 2007-03-30}}</ref> [[Norman Wilkinson (footballer born 1931)|Norman Wilkinson]] is the club's top goalscorer with 143 goals in all competitions. Wilkinson also holds the club record for goals scored in the League (127) and FA Cup (16).<ref name="York City´s all-time best Goal-scorers">{{cite web
| title = York City's all-time best Goal-scorers
| url = http://www.rivals.net/default.asp?sid=973&p=2&stid=8193451
| publisher = Minstermen.net
| accessdate = 2007-03-30}}</ref>

The club's widest victory margin in the league was their 9&ndash;1 win against [[Southport F.C.|Southport]] in the [[Football League Third Division North|Division Three North]] in 1957. Their heaviest defeat in the league was 12&ndash;0 against [[Chester City F.C.|Chester City]] in 1936.<ref name="Facts, Records and Statistics">{{cite web
| title = Facts, Records and Statistics
| url = http://www.yorkcityfc.com/history/history.php
| publisher = Red and Blue NET
| accessdate = 2007-04-23}}</ref>

York City's record home attendance is 28,123, for an FA Cup match against [[Huddersfield Town F.C.|Huddersfield Town]] on [[5 March]] [[1938]] at Bootham Crescent.<ref name="Facts, Records and Statistics"/> With the introduction of regulations enforcing all-seater stadiums, it is unlikely that this record will be beaten in the foreseeable future.

The highest transfer fee received for a York City player is £1&nbsp;million, from [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] for [[Jonathan Greening]] in March 1998, while the most spent by the club on a player was £140,000 for [[Adrian Randall]] from [[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]] in December 1995.<ref name="Facts, Records and Statistics"/>

